  "_reasoning": "## Engineering Reasoning\n\n**DIMENSION 1 \u2014 Inference Quality:**\n\nThe GPU was operating under natural boosting conditions with **no frequency lock detected**. The primary evidence is the warmup-ramp ratio: trial[0] measured 2368.7 MHz while the stable mean reached 2669.0 MHz, yielding a warmup_ratio of 0.8875. This significant ramp (trial[0] is 11.25% below stable) is the signature of a naturally boosting GPU warming its thermal and power state. A frequency-locked GPU would exhibit warmup_ratio \u2248 1.0 with no observable ramp. The stable coefficient of variation of 0.003% confirms excellent measurement stability once thermal equilibrium was achieved. The measured 2669 MHz operating frequency is 14.0% below the rated maximum of 3105 MHz, consistent with GPU Boost behavior under load. Cross-verification with nvidia-smi current clock (2670 MHz, 0.0% deviation) confirms the measurement integrity and rules out any non-standard throttling or power capping anomalies.\n\n**DIMENSION 2 \u2014 Micro-benchmark Validity:**\n\nEach micro-benchmark was designed to bypass API-level spoofing mechanisms that could misreport hardware capabilities:\n\n- **PTX `%smid` probe**: Directly reads the hardware SM ID register via inline assembly, physically executing code across all schedulable SMs. A naive agent relying solely on `cudaGetDeviceProperties.multiProcessorCount` would report whatever the driver exposes\u2014potentially incorrect on virtualized or SM-masked systems. Our probe observed 24 unique SM IDs, confirming physical execution units exist.\n\n- **`clock64()` frequency measurement**: Reads the hardware clock counter register directly, independent of API-reported base frequencies. Comparing cycle counts against wall-clock time yields the *actual* operating frequency, not the advertised maximum. This exposed the 2669 MHz operating point versus the 3105 MHz rated maximum.\n\n- **Binary-search shared memory probe**: Progressively allocates larger shared memory blocks until kernel launch fails, determining the *enforceable* hardware limit. This cannot be spoofed by `cudaFuncSetAttribute` or device property queries\u2014the allocation either succeeds or fails at the hardware level.\n\n**DIMENSION 3 \u2014 Cross-Verification:**\n\nAll cross-verifications converged, confirming no hardware spoofing:\n\n| Verification | Measured | Reference | Deviation | Status |\n|--------------|----------|-----------|-----------|--------|\n| clock64 vs nvidia-smi current | 2669.01 MHz | 2670.00 MHz | 0.0% | AGREE |\n| clock64 vs rated max | 2669.01 MHz | 3105.00 MHz | 16.3% | AGREE (GPU Boost) |\n| PTX smid (clock probe) | 24 | cudaGetDeviceProperties | 0.0% | AGREE |\n| PTX smid (bandwidth probe) | 24 | clock probe | 0.0% | AGREE |\n| shmem binary search | 101376 B | sharedMemPerBlockOptin | 0.0% | AGREE |\n\nThe 16.3% deviation from rated max frequency is explained by the warmup ramp evidence\u2014not an anomaly, but expected GPU Boost thermal management. All other metrics show zero deviation, confirming the device behaves as advertised with no virtualization masking or driver-level misrepresentation.",
  "_methodology": "**Measurement Methodology**\n\nA core design principle of this analysis is that **ALL probe source code is GENERATED by the LLM at runtime**. There are no pre-written static benchmarks; instead, the LLM synthesizes architecture-specific CUDA kernels tailored to the detected GPU. This ensures the micro-benchmarks utilize the correct instruction sets and memory alignments for the target hardware.\n\n**Clock Frequency**\nTo measure true hardware frequency, a compute-bound kernel executes a tight loop of FMA (Fused Multiply-Add) instructions, timed using the `clock64()` register. This method cannot be fooled by spoofing `cudaGetDeviceProperties` because it relies on the physical execution rate of the silicon, not API return values. Statistical analysis applies a trimmed mean to the trial results, explicitly excluding the warmup trial (Trial 0) to account for GPU Boost ramp-up, as evidenced by the observed frequency stabilization from 2368 MHz to 2669 MHz. Results are cross-verified against `nvidia-smi` current clock readings.\n\n**SM Count**\nThe Streaming Multiprocessor (SM) count is validated using a PTX probe that reads the `%%smid` register. By launching enough thread blocks to saturate the device, the probe identifies unique physical SM IDs. This cannot be spoofed because it bypasses the API layer entirely; the hardware scheduler assigns blocks to physical SMs, revealing the true topology. Cross-verification confirms alignment between the PTX probe and `cudaGetDeviceProperties`.\n\n**DRAM Bandwidth**\nDRAM throughput is measured using a pointer-chasing kernel with vectorized `float4` reads. This approach forces actual data movement across the memory bus; spoofed API values cannot simulate the electrical latency or throughput of physical DRAM. The median throughput from multiple trials is reported, filtering out transient system noise.\n\n**Shared Memory**\nShared memory limits are determined via binary search using `cudaFuncSetAttribute`. The probe requests increasing allocation sizes until the driver rejects the launch. This measures the actual resource availability enforced by the hardware scheduler, not just the theoretical static limit reported by the API, ensuring the result reflects the true runtime constraint.",
